  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Which is the best book for python?",
  "response": "The \"best\" book for learning Python depends on your current skill level and what you aim to achieve. Here\u2019s a curated list of highly recommended Python books tailored to different needs:\n\n---\n\n### **For Beginners:**\n1. **\"Automate the Boring Stuff with Python\" by Al Sweigart**  \n   - Focuses on practical applications like automating tasks, making it great for beginners.  \n   - Ideal for those who want to learn by doing.  \n   - Free to read online at [automatetheboringstuff.com](https://automatetheboringstuff.com/).\n\n2. **\"Python Crash Course\" by Eric Matthes**  \n   - A hands-on, project-based introduction to Python.  \n   - Covers basics and progresses to building projects like games and web apps.  \n   - Highly beginner-friendly and engaging.\n\n3. **\"Learning Python\" by Mark Lutz**  \n   - A comprehensive guide to Python\u2019s fundamentals.  \n   - Great for those who want a deep understanding of Python syntax and concepts.  \n   - Long and detailed, but worth it for serious learners.\n\n---\n\n### **Intermediate Learners:**\n4. **\"Fluent Python\" by Luciano Ramalho**  \n   - Focuses on writing idiomatic Python and mastering advanced features.  \n   - Perfect for those who understand the basics and want to write cleaner, more efficient code.  \n\n5. **\"Effective Python\" by Brett Slatkin**  \n   - Provides 90 specific ways to write better Python.  \n   - Great for refining your skills and understanding best practices.\n\n---\n\n### **Advanced Learners:**\n6. **\"Python Cookbook\" by David Beazley and Brian K. Jones**  \n   - A collection of recipes for solving common programming problems in Python.  \n   - Best for experienced programmers looking to deepen their knowledge.\n\n7. **\"Programming Python\" by Mark Lutz**  \n   - Focuses on real-world Python applications, including GUIs, databases, and networking.  \n   - Great for those who want to use Python for large-scale projects.\n\n---\n\n### **For Data Science and Machine Learning:**\n8. **\"Python for Data Analysis\" by Wes McKinney**  \n   - Written by the creator of pandas, this book focuses on data manipulation and analysis.  \n   - Perfect for aspiring data scientists.\n\n9. **\"Hands-On Machine Learning with Scikit-Learn, Keras, and TensorFlow\" by Aur\u00e9lien G\u00e9ron**  \n   - A practical guide to machine learning with Python tools.  \n   - Excellent for those interested in AI and ML.\n\n---\n\n### **For Web Development and Automation:**\n10. **\"Test-Driven Development with Python\" by Harry J.W. Percival**  \n    - Teaches web development with Django using a test-driven approach.  \n    - Great for building web applications.\n\n11. **\"Web Scraping with Python\" by Ryan Mitchell**  \n    - Focuses on extracting data from websites using Python.  \n    - Ideal for those interested in web scraping and automation.\n\n---\n\n### **My Top Pick for Beginners:**  \n**\"Automate the Boring Stuff with Python\"** is an excellent starting point if you\u2019re new to programming and want to learn by solving real-world problems.\n\n**For Intermediate/Advanced Users:**  \n**\"Fluent Python\"** is a must-read to master Python\u2019s advanced features and write elegant code.\n\nLet me know if you\u2019d like more tailored recommendations!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
